ie, Frankrijk","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Winchester, Hampshire, England":"Winchester, Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wales":"Wales"},"en":{"Abt 1060–Abt 1119":"about 1060–about 1119","1060–1119":"1060–1119","1075–1187":"1075–1187","1087–1155":"1087–1155","1088–Male":"1088–Deceased","1089–Male":"1089–Deceased","1091–Male":"1091–Deceased","1094–Female":"1094–Deceased","1040–Male":"1040–Deceased","1091":"1091","1066":"1066","1088":"1088","1187":"1187","1087":"1087","1075":"1075","1040":"1040","1094":"1094","Abt 1119":"about 1119","1060":"1060","1089":"1089","1155":"1155","before 1087":"before 1087","about 1087":"about 1087","Abt 1060":"about 1060","1119":"1119","Vermandois, Aisne, Picardy, France":"Aisne, Picardie, France","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Winchester, Hampshire, England":"Winchester, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Herbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Winchester","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city in Hampshire, so named from the addition of Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘Roman fort or walled city’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’) to the Romano-British name <i>Venta</i>, of disputed origin.","History: John Winchester was admitted a freeman in Brookline, MA, in 1637. Oliver Winchester (1810–80), owner of the arms company that produced the Winchester rifle, was his fifth-generation descendant, born in Boston."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Herbert of Winchester Chamberlain of England was born about 1060, in Aisne, Picardie, France as the son of Henry. He married Emma de Blois before 1087, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. His occupation is listed as tenant-in-chief (under king henry ii) in Winchester, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom. He died about 1119, in Winc